This is related to Logging configuration.

See https://github.com/eclipse/jetty.project/issues/6186

Your `HttpCookie` Logger is not configured by the time the offending code is run.


&gt; ```
&gt; -Dorg.eclipse.jetty.util.log.class=org.eclipse.jetty.util.log.StdErrLog
&gt; -Dorg.eclipse.jetty.LEVEL=DEBUG
&gt; ```

This will work only on the initial JVM.  If your build or instance or configuration has something that forces a forked JVM, this won&#39;t be carried over to the forked JVM.

&gt; ``` java
&gt; import org.eclipse.jetty.util.log.Log;
&gt; import org.eclipse.jetty.util.log.StdErrLog;
&gt; Log.setLog(new StdErrLog());
&gt; ```

This will work, but only if it&#39;s literally the very first thing you do in your program.

``` java
// These are the ONLY two import statements with references
// to `org.eclipse.jetty` allowed in here, any other 
// import statements risk causing the logging to initialize
// before your efforts below kick in.
import org.eclipse.jetty.util.log.Log;
import org.eclipse.jetty.util.log.StdErrLog;

public static void main(String args[]) {
    Log.setLog(new StdErrLog());
    // the rest of your startup.
}
```

Because this is Logging, the configuration has to happen as early as possible, and be configured regardless of initialization / forking of
the JVM.

Do this instead.

Create a `jetty-logging.properties` and put it in your classpath somewhere, in the root of one of your classloader references (directory or jar) is all that&#39;s needed.

Since you said `embedded-jetty`, put in the root of your jar that has the Main-Class.

Contents of ...

``` lang-ini
org.eclipse.jetty.util.log.class=org.eclipse.jetty.util.log.StdErrLog
org.eclipse.jetty.LEVEL=DEBUG
# You can even configure specific trees to be less noisy.
org.eclipse.jetty.http.HttpCookie.LEVEL=INFO
```

